{"key":"processedPost-13655149","value":{"id":13655149,"first":13654142,"last":13726648,"when":1292772298,"utime":"12/19/10 05:24 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>Wise Toad said:</strong><br />Instead of taking the whole filter and placing it between the lid and the ring can one simply cut it into small squares and attach them to the lid with silicone like everybody does with tyvek?</blockquote><br />This is a very bad idea.<br />The synthetic filter disks have an extremely small micron size pore structure and you won't get sufficient gas exchange through small pieces.&nbsp; You're better to get new lids and drill four 1/8\" holes in each, and then use the filter over the top of that.&nbsp; This way, the entire filter can exchange gasses instead of just a small part.&nbsp; <br />In addition, there's no way to clean the bottom of a filter that's glued down to a lid, and this is the side exposed to the grains.<br />Filters always should go above the lids, not below where they're exposed to the grains when you shake.<br />RR","title":"Re: Synthetic filter disk question"}}